Tablut
a 20-minute war game for two players
EQUIPMENT:
You’ll need 3 kinds of markers: 16 of one kind, 8 of
a second kind, and 1 of a third: the king.
HOW TO PLAY:
One player defends the king from the other. The
defender puts the king on the middle square (the
“konakis”) and their other 8 markers on the squares
marked with circles. The attacker puts their markers
on squares marked with x’s.
Players take turns moving one of their markers.
horizontally or vertically, as many spaces as they
like, until they come to an occupied space or the
edge of the board.
Only the king may enter or cross the konakis.
CAPTURING:
A marker is taken when opposing markers occupy
both adjacent spaces in a row or column. Markers
may move to a space between two opponents
without being taken. The king is captured when all
4 adjacent spaces are occupied by enemies, or if
there are 3 adjacent enemies and the 4th adjacent
space is the konakis.
WINNING:
The defender wins if the king is moved to a
square on the edge. The attacker wins if the king
is captured.
POLITENESS:
If the defender sees that the king has a path to
the edge, they must say “raichi”. If they see two
paths, they must say “tuichu”. This is the honorable
behavior described in Frithof’s Saga; cursed be
all who do otherwise; may their beards fall out!
HISTORY:
This is a game from Lapland, described by Linneus.
Its board and initial layout are similar to what
is known about Hnefetafl, the lost Bronze-Age
game, which was played on a larger board.
